Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
This morning in Pleasanton, I had the pleasure of joining city and community leaders to break ground on a project that marks a bold step forward for Atascosa County.

Thanks to a $1.71 million federal investment from the USDA Rural Development Community Facilities Program, Pleasanton Municipal Airport is building a new hangar. It will house up to eight aircraft, generate revenue, and expand services for local businesses, freight operations, and emergency response. Together, these efforts are strengthening the city‚Äôs role as a key part of our regional aviation network.

A heartfelt thank you to those whose leadership and hard work made this day possible: Mayor JR Gallegos, Mayor Pro-tem Joey Macon, the Pleasanton City Council, Bond Counsel Carey Troell, USDA partner Betty Soto, Brian Cope of COPE Engineering, Roger Wells of Wells Construction, City Manager Johnny Huizar, Finance Director Raquel Navarro, Assistant Finance Director Cassie Garcia, City Attorney Bobby Maldonado, Airport Manager JJ Roberts, and Ernie Gonzalez of EMC Strategy Group.
Your dedication to this city is laying the foundation for smart, lasting growth.

This hangar represents more than just infrastructure. It reflects the momentum building in Pleasanton and the bright future we are working toward together!

Name: Sherrill, Mikie
text:
I‚Äôm deeply concerned by the violence earlier this week at the aid distribution center in southern Gaza, which resulted in one death and dozens of injuries. Aid must be delivered swiftly and safely to civilians across Gaza.

The unchecked humanitarian crisis in Gaza is unacceptable and the U.S. has not done enough to address it. During my last visit to the Rafah Border Crossing, I witnessed first hand the miles of aid trucks being held at the border and raised my concerns to both President Biden and P.M. Netanyahu.¬†

I urge the Trump administration to collaborate with the Israeli government and humanitarian organizations working in Gaza to establish a safer and more effective approach to delivering aid, while doing everything possible to ensure Hamas does not steal these resources from civilians. Failing to adequately address the humanitarian needs of the people of Gaza is a failure to uphold U.S. values, increases Hamas‚Äôs support, and prolongs the war. It is vital that both parties reach an agreement leading to an immediate ceasefire, the release of all remaining hostages ‚Äî including four Americans ‚Äî who have been held for over 600 days, and an end to this brutal war.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

Gregory Singleton, the dean of academic programs at the Opportunities Industrialization Center of Rocky Mount, is a proud Rocky Mount resident who has dedicated his life to education and the power of second chances. 

He began his journey as a part-time instructor at Craven Correctional Institution and later launched the Keys to Freedom program. Gregory founded the Craven Pamlico Reentry Council, and his inspiring vision is now realized as he develops similar councils in four neighboring counties. His relentless efforts have significantly reduced recidivism rates and uplifted public safety throughout eastern North Carolina.

In recognition of his impactful work, Gregory received the 2025 MyFutureNC Champion for Attainment award and was acknowledged by the Governor. He has also been honored as the North Carolina Community College Staff Person of the Year. We are glad to recognize Gregory for his work helping to transform the East. 

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories from across our district that shine a light on the heroes among us. Today, we honor the life and service of Alec Campbell‚Äîa DCNR Resource Ranger at Tyler State Park, a devoted father, and a true public servant‚Äîwhose life was tragically cut short this past weekend at just 38 years old.
 
Alec‚Äôs passing is a heartbreaking loss‚Äînot only to those who knew and loved him but to our entire community. Rangers like Alec rarely seek spotlight but their service is essential. They are the quiet guardians of our natural spaces‚Äîeducators, protectors, first responders, and stewards‚Äîoften putting themselves in harm‚Äôs way to ensure the safety and well-being of others.
 
Alec embodied that spirit of service in every sense. Along with restoring trails, removing invasive species, and planting natives, perhaps his most important work was leading volunteer and youth projects that have left a lasting mark on Tyler State Park. He was a patient teacher, a passionate conservationist, and a calming presence for visitors from all walks of life. Whether working with young Scouts or guiding students through the forest, Alec always made people feel seen, heard, and safe.
 
His background in psychology, his gift for connection, and his deep love for the outdoors made him more than a ranger‚Äîhe was a bridge between people and nature, between learning and healing.
 
It‚Äôs easy to take that kind of service for granted. But we shouldn‚Äôt. Because our parks don‚Äôt care for themselves. Our trails don‚Äôt repair themselves. And when someone gets lost or needs help, it‚Äôs rangers like Alec who answer the call.
 
Please join me in extending our prayers and condolences to Alec‚Äôs wife, Rena, their two young boys, Calder and Miles, and his @DCNRnews family. Let us honor Alec by remembering the value of quiet service‚Äîand by recognizing the brave men and women like him who dedicate their lives to preserving, protecting, and serving our community every single day.
 
May his memory be a guiding light in the places he loved.

text:
It was a pleasure to join the community in Hebbronville for a special evening celebrating our local authors and storytellers.

A sincere thank you to County Judge Juan Carlos Guerra, Sheriff Alarcon, our County Commissioners, and all of our local officials. Deep appreciation as well to Lupita Almaraz, the Historical Commission, and the Museum Foundation of Hebbronville for organizing such a meaningful event.

In a place like Hebbronville, where history, heritage, and heart run deep, we were reminded of the importance of preserving our stories. The authors we honored last night have contributed more than just words on a page. They have helped document the culture, memory, and resilience of this region.

I was proud to present each of the local authors with a Congressional Certificate of Recognition in appreciation of their work and dedication to telling the stories that shape our communities.

Thank you again to everyone who made the evening possible, and to the writers whose voices continue to make an impact both here at home and beyond.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today, I held a press conference in Laredo to stand with our community in the fight against the opioid and fentanyl crisis. This is a crisis that has taken far too many lives, but one that this community is confronting with courage and unity.

Together, we recognized the deep toll this epidemic has taken on our families, our neighborhoods, and our way of life. Many lives in Webb County have been lost to fentanyl. Each one was a loved and valued member of our community. But in the face of that pain, Laredo did not stay silent or still. You came together, took action, and chose to fight back.

Thanks to the extraordinary leadership of individuals like Mayor Dr. Victor D. Trevi√±o, Deputy Fire Chief Roberto Gonzalez, Police Chief Miguel A. Rodriguez Jr., and Sheriff Martin Cuellar, along with our educators, health professionals, law enforcement, and countless community partners, overdose deaths in Webb County dropped by 52 percent in just one year. That is real progress and a testament to what is possible when a community works together.

Nearly five million dollars in federal support has helped fund prevention, treatment, and recovery efforts, including expanded Narcan access. But the driving force behind this change is right here in Laredo. It is in the people who refused to lose another life without a fight.

As part of today‚Äôs conference, I was proud to present Congressional Certificates of Recognition to several law enforcement agencies and community organizations for their outstanding efforts in combating substance abuse and saving lives. Their dedication has made a lasting impact and continues to protect and uplift our community.

To everyone making a difference on the ground, thank you. You are proving that hope is stronger than fear and that even in the face of crisis, Laredo leads with compassion, strength, and resolve.

The Autocrat Social and Pleasure Club, founded in 1909 and reorganized in 1914 under Arthur Boisdore, is one of the oldest Black social aid and pleasure clubs in New Orleans. From its longtime home at 1725 St. Bernard Avenue, it has been a cornerstone of Seventh Ward culture ‚Äî hosting legendary jazz musicians, supporting civil rights leaders like A.P. Tureaud, and serving as a proud community hub for over a century.

Today, as the U.S. Congressman representing this historic site, I had the amazing honor of presenting a Congressional Record and Proclamation to the members of the Autocrat Social and Pleasure Club. It is a privilege to celebrate their enduring legacy and their unshakable place in the heart of New Orleans.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
When Russia invaded Ukraine in Feb 2022, Congress was briefed repeatedly with a pressure campaign.

They told us over and over that Putin was just like Hitler and he would quickly take Ukraine then Poland next and he was so crazy that he would steam roll across Europe.

And that we must send as much money, weapons, and even put US troops on the ground to stop this mad man.

I never believed the lies and refused from day one to vote to fund it because just like with the Covid ‚Äúpandemic‚Äù it was easy to find the truth and dispel their manipulations.

3 years and 3 months later it‚Äôs still the same war they have been fighting since 2014, and Russia only controls 20% of Ukraine. 

Congress has been lied to in briefings many times just like the American people have been lied to.

All in manipulations to support wars and issues that have absolutely nothing to do with our people, our security, and our future.

Yet the taxpayer funding that has been doled out by the trillions always enriches the military industrial complex and special interest NGOs and all the people that figure out how to get contracts off the latest grift.

What do the American people get?

$36 trillion dollars in debt.

Our fathers, uncles, brothers, sons, cousins, and friends killed or forever injured from foreign wars.

A federal government and elected leaders obsessed with foreign causes and conflicts going on taxpayer funded codels to inject themselves into the grift.

A never ending flow of lobbyists going through revolving doors of Congressmen‚Äôs offices with funding requests that ‚Äúprotect jobs‚Äù in our districts.

And mainly a government that is too broke to fix our own infrastructure, education system, mental health and drug crisis, and invest in our children‚Äôs futures. 

American people, you aren‚Äôt angry enough at what your leaders have done to you and lied to you about for decades now. 

And you are the only ones who can truly fix it.

Name: McClain, Lisa C.
text:
This month, I am honored to recognize Sergeant First Class Christopher ‚ÄúChris‚Äù Leidlein as the MI-09 Veteran of the Month. A resident of Applegate, Michigan, SFC Leidlein answered the call to serve his country in September 1991 when he enlisted in the United States Army.¬†

He began his military career at Fort Sill in Oklahoma, where he completed his Basic and Advanced Individual Training as a Fire Support Specialist. His first assignment was at Fort Richardson in Alaska, where he participated in military exercises across Alaska, Thailand, and California. SFC Leidlein was also stationed at Fort Knox in Kentucky and Fort Drum in New York. He deployed to Panama as a Platoon Fire Support Sergeant and served in multiple combat deployments in Afghanistan and Iraq.¬†

His leadership and bravery were critical throughout his career, as he earned two Bronze Stars, the Meritorious Service Medal, a Presidential Unit Citation, a NATO Medal, multiple Army Achievement Medals, and Army Commendation Medals. He also trained over 15,000 reserve soldiers.¬†

SFC Leidlein built a legacy of courage, innovation, and selfless leadership. His mentorship of thousands of soldiers and cadets helped shape the future of America‚Äôs defense forces.

It is an honor to represent an exceptional veteran like SFC Leidlein. His dedication to our nation and community is valiant. He has truly made Michigan's 9th Congressional District proud. Thank you, and congratulations, Sergeant First Class Christopher ‚ÄúChris‚Äù Leidlein.

Name: Budzinski, Nikki
text:
Yesterday, President Trump took a victory lap, claiming he single-handedly saved American steel ‚Äî but he failed to mention Illinois, failed to mention Granite City Works, and failed to consult the hundreds of workers who built this industry as a bedrock of our community.

While the details of this ‚Äúdeal‚Äù remain murky, any agreement struck between President Trump and Nippon is unenforceable unless steelworkers are at the table. The current collective bargaining agreement requires robust investment to keep Granite City competitive worldwide. Given that the current proposal fails to meet those standards, it simply cannot move forward.

Granite City deserves more than broken promises and publicity stunts. I‚Äôm fighting to ensure that at least $500 million of the $14 billion deal is dedicated to upgrading Granite City Works with a modern granulation system and the infrastructure needed for workers to thrive. It's unfathomable that the initial proposal includes billions for new facilities yet leaves behind the steelworkers at Granite City Works ‚Äì men and women who have honorably served U.S. Steel since 1927.

From my very first day in Congress, fighting for Granite City has remained at the top of my agenda. Let‚Äôs be clear: any deal that sidelines our community or neglects existing facilities is a nonstarter. It cannot ‚Äì and will not ‚Äì stand.

Name: Fine, Randy
text:
I couldn't sleep last night.  I can't sleep on my plane to DC.  Too much sadness, anger, and fear.  

I‚Äôm not supposed to be in Congress.  Seven months ago, I got elected to the Florida Senate.  I worked hard to get there.   I was excited thinking I'd have a four year break before another election.  

I couldn‚Äôt have imagined that two weeks later, I‚Äôd get called to run for Congress.  It wasn‚Äôt part of my plan.  It wasn't part of my family's.  

But G-d puts us where He wants us to be.   And as I sit on my flight to DC this morning, struggling to comprehend that I live in a country where Jews can be burned because they are Jews, I know at least one reason He put me here.  

80 years ago they burned us too.  Call your Jewish friends today.  They will tell you that it feels like we are being hunted.  That it is open season.  We are experiencing anti-Semitic hate unlike anything we have ever experienced. 

But there is hope. 

Florida is the safest place in America to be Jewish, and that is not by coincidence.   Together with my friends in the House and Senate -- and they are more than colleagues to me -- we passed bill after bill, most that I initially wrote by hand.  

It came at a cost.  Two people made death threats against my family that landed them in prison.  

It hasn't gone perfectly.  There are still issues.  And some could have done more.   But there has been massive progress. 

I am new in Congress, and as the guy who just showed up, I'm as low on the totem pole as you can be. 

But I am going to work with whoever is willing and whoever I have to in order to solve this problem.  And I will fight whoever opposes us, including anyone on my side who gets in my way.   

I did not come up with my nickname, but it does suit me. 

My power has always been my voice, and I won't be afraid to use it. 

Those who try to shout me down -- like the lunatics who comment here ‚Äî the leftists, the Nazis, the Muslim terrorists, the woke right, and those who I beat along the way ‚Äî every comment gives me more strength and more purpose. 

It refires the forge that was lit when I was a 13 year old boy facing my own trials of antisemitism. 

So keep it coming.   You just make me more determined.  You fuel the forge. 

My plane is getting ready to land in DC.  The battle is right in front of me. 

I am ready to fight.  I know we will win.  

Because we have a secret weapon:

We have G-d on our side.

#BombsAway

text:
PA-1 is home to many remarkable women‚Äîand yesterday, we celebrated the next generation of trailblazers at the Sandy Run Service Unit #624 Court of Awards and Bridging Ceremony in Yardley. 

Abigail Greenberg, a junior at Pennsbury High School, received the prestigious Gold Award for her outstanding ‚ÄúWomen in STEM‚Äù initiative‚Äîdeveloping workbooks and teacher guides, leading student workshops, and launching a digital campaign to inspire girls to see themselves as future scientists. Her curriculum has now been adopted by the Pennsbury School District, leaving a legacy that will continue to empower students for years to come.

We also recognized Silver Award recipients:

Gretchen Hill, for launching a hygiene kit initiative to support our neighbors in need and creating a guide to help others replicate her efforts.

Emma Chung, for leading teams of volunteers in creating handmade blankets for our local animal shelters. 

And Lilly Marie Dillon, for making over 160 heating pads for rescued kittens‚Äîand teaching others to carry her mission forward.

Each of these young women is a doer, a builder, and a leader‚Äîthe kind of role models every community hopes for, and our country needs.

Join me in applauding their achievements, and in thanking Mary Mooney and the entire Sandy Run community for nurturing leadership in the exceptional young women of PA-1.

Name: Mullin, Markwayne
text:
I've seen your questions and comments: How do we codify DOGE cuts ASAP? ‚¨áÔ∏è

One MAJOR way: We're working with the Trump @WhiteHouse on an upcoming @DOGE cuts package to CANCEL wasteful spending using something called the rescissions process.

Here's how it works:

Under the Impoundment Control Act, we've asked the Trump administration to send Congress a package of previously appropriated federal funds for us to eliminate. 

Note: this rescissions package only requires a simple majority vote (aka 51 of our 53 @SenateGOP seats). 

Among other cuts, the upcoming rescissions package targets billions in wasteful foreign aid spending.

Now, once the Trump administration sends this rescissions package over, by law, Congress has 45 DAYS to review the funding and strike it down.

@elonmusk and @POTUS have done excellent work with DOGE. It's time to make cuts PERMANENT. More to come.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today I was proud to stand at the @ThePortofCC as an appropriator to celebrate a major milestone for South Texas, the completion of a federal  $625 million dollar channel improvement project. This effort will power our economy, strengthen national security, and expand our global competitiveness.

This is not just infrastructure. It is an investment in opportunity. It shows what is possible when we build smart and work together for a stronger, safer, and more prosperous future.

As one of only three Strategic Military Seaports in Texas, the Port of Corpus Christi is vital to both our economic strength and national defense. With this project complete, the Port is now ready to lead in energy independence and global trade.

Corpus Christi has become the nation‚Äôs largest energy export gateway, due in part to my working on legislation with Rep. Joe Barton to lift the U.S. oil export ban in 2015. I have also worked to ensure the federal government not only funds ports like this but truly understands their importance.

This achievement reflects true partnership. Thank you to Congressman Michael Cloud, former Congressman Solomon Ortiz, Brigadier General George H. Walter for your leadership.

Together with the Port of Laredo, Corpus Christi forms a vital trade corridor linking our region to the world!

To every worker, engineer, and advocate who made this happen, thank you. You built more than a channel. You built a legacy.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Over the weekend, the White House Director of the Office of Management and Budget and Project 2025 author Russell Vought spent his morning on CNN lying about the Republican budget bill.

Let's break down this segment üßµ

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
In case you're not familiar with Vought, he's a right-wing Trump loyalist who's worked for him for years.

He wrote a chapter for Project 2025 arguing for the "aggressive use of the vast powers of the executive branch."

So what were his lies?

https://t.co/L8lR2P3bI5

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
2. He says that "1 out of every $5 or $6 in Medicaid is improper."

Clearly his implication is that because of this data, it's justified to cut ~20% of Medicaid.

What he chooses to leave out is that "improper" is a specific term used by the government.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
1. The Republican budget bill "preserves and protects" social safety net programs.

A blatant lie as I'm unaware of how cutting over a trillion dollars and kicking millions of Americans off health care is "preserving and protecting" this program.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Classifying payments as "improper" is one of the ways the government measures administrative performance in Medicaid, Medicare, and other federal programs.

As the Georgetown McCourt School of Public Policy points out, improper payments are not fraud.

https://t.co/JZGtXWt6rp

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
According to the agency that administers Medicaid, CMS, improper payments¬†can¬†be¬†overpayments,¬†underpayments,¬†or¬†payments¬†where¬†insufficient¬†information¬†was provided to determine whether a payment was proper.

https://t.co/W2Itg64SL8

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
CMS also recorded that the improper payment rate last year was just over 5%, nowhere near what Vought falsely cites to justify cutting hundreds of billions of dollars.

https://t.co/XiffKtB9Io

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
3. "We need more work requirements because there's too many people on Medicaid and SNAP not working."

The only part that "works" about work requirements is that they kick more people off programs with new red tape. 

More red tape = people are less inclined to use the program.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Take Arkansas. They implemented work requirements and 25% of people subject to them lost coverage because of the reporting and documentation requirements.

This created a bureaucracy (which Trump has attacked) that directly led to less coverage.
https://t.co/bak86IOpPX

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
4. "There's undocumented immigrants on Medicaid."

This could be its own thread, but for now, let's be clear: undocumented immigrants are already not allowed to be on Medicaid.

https://t.co/6W31mE7Ma8

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Which brings us to his final point:

5. "No one will lose coverage."

When your whole argument is that the cuts are only to prevent "fraud, waste, and abuse" and "kick undocumented migrants off Medicaid," but the data doesn't support it, who will it hurt?

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
It WILL hurt Americans who rely on Medicaid for healthcare.

It WILL hurt Americans who work at hospitals that shut down.

It WILL hurt Americans in rural communities that'll no longer have access to healthcare.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
The Center for American Progress identified nearly 200 rural hospitals that were kept open by Medicaid funding.

If the Republican budget bill is signed into law, they could all close down.
https://t.co/6s3ysOg7Gh

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Don't just take my word for it. 

Even Republicans like Senator Josh Hawley have acknowledged all of this already. 

https://t.co/b2JwwnTvRY

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Russell Vought had no shame or second thoughts about lying to the American people about this bill.

It's because they know it's unpopular and they're hoping Americans are not informed.

Don't let them win.

Name: Smith, Tina
text:
Sue Abderholden is a force of nature, and her advocacy for people experiencing mental health challenges is unmatched.  She started at the grassroots, working for Paul Wellstone and then working with kids with developmental disabilities.  As Executive Director of NAMI Minnesota she passed laws to  require mental health training for teachers, expand crisis and early intervention services, strengthen how insurance companies cover mental health care.  As Sue retires from leading NAMI, we owe her a huge debt of gratitude.

We have made progress these last few years, like launching the 9-8-8 hotline nationwide, and we have huge challenges ahead.  With Sue as our mentor and model, we will keep on fighting back against attacks on the largest source of insurance for children‚Äôs mental health treatment in the nation (Medicaid), and renewed efforts by people up to the Secretary of HHS to stigmatize folks with mental illness and behavior health challenges.

Congratulations Sue as you begin a new phase of your life, and thank you so much for your service.

Name: Pressley, Ayanna
text:
Yesterday, while ICE officials smugly touted the arrest of nearly 1,500 people in Massachusetts over the past month, I convened immigrant families from my district who have been unjustly harmed by Trump‚Äôs cruel and unlawful mass deportation agenda.

All across the Massachusetts 7th, ICE raids have robbed us of family members and our collective sense of security and belonging.

And the stories we heard were harrowing.

We heard from Kenia from Chelsea, who was driving to a Mother's Day church service with her husband Daniel when ICE agents in unmarked vehicles ambushed them, broke the passenger side window, forcefully extracted Daniel from the car, and slammed his face on the sidewalk while their three children watched in horror.

"We are devastated. No one should live through this," Kenia said. "He needs to come home."

We also heard from Mercedes, an East Boston resident, whose family is struggling after her husband Jose was arrested at work and detained for two days at an ICE facility in Burlington. Jose was living here legally with Temporary Protected Status but was told by the ICE agents who detained him that "only people born here have rights."

"We are deeply traumatized," she told us. "My husband and I can't sleep. I'm afraid to go out. I'm afraid to take my daughter to school. Our 12-year-old daughter who was born in this country has anxiety attacks."

And we heard from Yolanda, a Randolph resident, whose husband Santo was taken through the back exit of a police precinct and handed off to ICE officers, but not before he was mocked by the officers on duty and told to "go meet his new family." Santo was shipped off to a detention center in Louisiana, where he has struggled to control his diabetes and hypertension, and has reported that the medical staff and officers make fun of him because of his English and have failed to properly treat his conditions.

These horrific raids have never been about "safety" or "law and order," as the Trump Administration claims ‚Äî they have always been about terrorizing immigrant families, abusing power, and sowing fear in our communities.

They are absolutely shameful and in many cases, unlawful and in violation of folks' constitutional rights.

Donald Trump is a dictator who wants a citizenry that is inactive and indifferent to the suffering of their neighbors, including our immigrant families in the Massachusetts 7th. But we will not stand by while he and ICE carry out their unlawful mass deportation agenda and rip our families apart.

We stand with our immigrant neighbors. Children should not live in fear of their parents disappearing. And elders should not live in fear of going to the grocery store or their faith house.

I was proud to convene this urgent and timely discussion about how we can push back against this harmful agenda, uplift impacted families, and share resources. And I am grateful to our advocates, families, and local partners for joining us.

Together, we say: Hands off our immigrant neighbors.

While we do not know if the agents  presented any warrants before detaining them, any apprehension without due process, including no warrants, is unfair and illegal. Chicago is a sanctuary city, and in Illinois, the Trust Act prohibits State or local law enforcement‚Äôs participation in federal immigration enforcement. 

My staff and I will continue in communication with advocacy organizations and local elected officials as this case develops.‚Äù
